Task 1 — Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic

Tool Used
Canva (canva.com) — I used Canva because it's free,browser-based, and honestly produces much better results than anything
I'd make in PowerPoint. No installation needed either, which was helpful.

What the Infographic Covers

The infographic is a single-page visual resource split into three sections:

1. What Digital Literacy Actually Is — I broke it into following pillars: finding information, communicating online, creating content, 
staying safe. 
I wanted to avoid just copy-pasting a textbook definition and explain each one simply instead.

2. Useful Tools for Students — Tools grouped by category: professional profiles (GitHub - Projects, LinkedIn - Networking, 
Kaggle - Data Science), coding practice (HackerRank, CodeChef), collaboration (Google Drive, Google Forms), and 
(NPTEL, Coursera) for skill development and learning. Things we'll actually use in college.

3. Safe Internet Habits — Password safety, two-factor authentication, phishing awareness, creating strong passwords
and UPI scam basics.
I kept it practical rather than overly technical.
